{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:48:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.23,0.06,0.03,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49112"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34147"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2631"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49112"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents with acute onset of agitation and confusion. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears flushed with a temperature of 38.9\u00b0C. His pupils are dilated and minimally reactive to light. His mucous membranes are dry. While being examined, he reaches out as if picking at imaginary objects. His parents report that just prior to the onset of symptoms, he was playing unsupervised in the garden, where Jimson weed grows wild.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alkaloid poisoning","Sympathomimetic toxidrome","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxidrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation and the history of exposure to Jimson weed, this child is exhibiting classic signs of \u003Cstrong\u003Eanticholinergic toxidrome\u003C/strong\u003E. Jimson weed (\u003Cem\u003EDatura stramonium\u003C/em\u003E) contains potent anticholinergic alkaloids such as atropine, scopolamine, and hyoscyamine. Ingestion leads to competitive antagonism of muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, resulting in the toxidrome characterized by the saying \u0022blind as a bat\u0022 (mydriasis), \u0022mad as a hatter\u0022 (delirium, agitation, hallucinations), \u0022red as a beet\u0022 (flushing), \u0022hot as a hare\u0022 (hyperthermia), \u0022dry as a bone\u0022 (dry mucous membranes, anhidrosis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaloid poisoning\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad term that could encompass anticholinergic toxidrome, as the toxic compounds in Jimson weed are indeed alkaloids. However, this term is less specific and doesn\u0027t fully capture the distinct clinical picture presented. Many alkaloids have different mechanisms of action and produce varied clinical effects, so this term alone doesn\u0027t provide as much diagnostic precision as anticholinergic toxidrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathomimetic toxidrome\u003C/strong\u003E from agents like cocaine and amphetamines would present similarly with agitation, hyperthermia, and mydriasis. However, this child was exposed to an anticholinergic agent, not a sympathomimetic. Additionally, sympathomimetic toxicity typically causes diaphoresis rather than dry skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition caused by excess serotonin agonism, usually due to drug interactions. It presents with altered mental status, autonomic instability, hyperthermia, and neuromuscular hyperactivity (hyperreflexia, clonus). The absence of serotonergic drug exposure makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an idiosyncratic reaction to antipsychotic medications and other dopamine antagonists. It is characterized by the triad of altered mental status, muscular rigidity, and autonomic instability. The lack of neuroleptic exposure and muscular rigidity makes this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Jimson weed contains anticholinergic alkaloids that can cause an anticholinergic toxidrome in overdose, characterised by \u0022blind as a bat, mad as a hatter, red as a beet, hot as a hare, dry as a bone\u0022.","Treatment of anticholinergic toxicity is primarily supportive, with benzodiazepines for agitation and cooling for hyperthermia. Physostigmine is an antidote but rarely used."],"references":["Anticholinergic Syndrome. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital clinical practice guidelines [online]. 2017 [Accessed 2024 Jun 24]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Anticholinergic_Syndrome/","Chan K. Jimson Weed Poisoning\u2014A Case Report. Perm J. 2002 Fall;6(4):28\u201330. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6220643/","Vanderhoff BT, Mosser KH. Jimson weed toxicity: management of anticholinergic plant ingestion. Am Fam Physician. 1992;46(2):526-30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1636566/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34147"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34147"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T16:40:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T20:54:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only